{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487064"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"242"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/242"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.54,0.06,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/242"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"276"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42036"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with palpitations. Two hours ago, he was discharged from the endoscopy suite following an elective endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography for removal of a gallstone from the bile duct. The procedure was uncomplicated. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He denies chest pain or shortness of breath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears comfortable. His pulse rate is 140/min (regular), blood pressure 110/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His GCS if 15. An electrocardiogram shows monomorphic ventricular tachycardia (Image). His vital signs remain unchanged over 30 minutes of observation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electrical cardioversion","Intravenous amiodarone","Intravenous magnesium sulfate","Intravenous lignocaine","Intravenous metoprolol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hemodynamically stable monomorphic ventricular tachycardia (VT). The management approach depends on hemodynamic stability and the presence of end-organ symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous amiodarone i\u003C/strong\u003Es the first-line agent for chemical cardioversion in stable VT. As a broad-spectrum Class III antiarrhythmic, amiodarone prolongs repolarization, decreases excitability, and suppresses reentrant circuits, making it the most effective option for terminating monomorphic VT in structurally normal and abnormal hearts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended dosing regimen is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoading dose: 300 mg IV over 1 hour\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaintenance infusion: 900 mg IV over 24 hours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient should be closely monitored, as VT may progress to hemodynamic instability, requiring escalation of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectrical cardioversion \u003C/strong\u003Eis indicated if the patient develops signs of instability, including hypotension, chest pain, pulmonary edema, or altered mental status. While synchronized cardioversion is highly effective, pharmacological treatment is preferred first in a stable patient. If amiodarone fails to terminate VT or the patient deteriorates, immediate cardioversion should be performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium sulfate \u003C/strong\u003Eis primarily used for torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT) in the setting of QT prolongation and is not first-line for monomorphic VT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELignocaine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a second-line agent for VT, particularly in the context of acute myocardial infarction. However, it is less effective than amiodarone for sustained VT and is not the preferred initial treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for monomorphic VT, as it primarily treats supraventricular tachycardias (SVT) and may worsen hypotension without reliably terminating VT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial stabilization, identifying precipitating factors is essential. Given this patient\u2019s recent ERCP, potential contributors include electrolyte disturbances (hypokalaemia, hypomagnesemia) or peri-procedural myocardial ischemia, both of which can trigger VT. Investigations should include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum electrolytes (potassium, magnesium, calcium)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiac biomarkers to assess for myocardial ischemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEchocardiography to evaluate for structural heart disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IV amiodarone is first-line therapy for haemodynamically stable ventricular tachycardia","Electrical cardioversion is indicated for unstable VT with hypotension, chest pain, or altered mental status","Regular monitoring of haemodynamic status is essential as stable VT can deteriorate rapidly"],"references":["Al-Khatib SM, Stevenson WG, Ackerman MJ, et al. 2017 AHA/ACC/HRS guideline for management of patients with ventricular arrhythmias and the prevention of sudden cardiac death. Heart Rhythm. 2018;15(10):e73-e189. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29097319","Pedersen CT, Kay GN, Kalman J, et al. EHRA/HRS/APHRS expert consensus on ventricular arrhythmias. Heart Rhythm. 2014;11(10):e166-96. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25173164","Australian Resuscitation Council (ARC). Guideline 11.9 \u2013 Managing acute dysrhythmias Melbourne, VIC: Australian Resuscitation Council; 2009.\u00a0Available at: https://resus.org.au/guidelines/","Neumar RW, Otto CW, Link MS, et al. Part 8: adult advanced cardiovascular life support: 2010 American Heart Association Guidelines for Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation and Emergency Cardiovascular Care. Circulation. 2010;122(18 Suppl 3):S729-67. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20956224"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"242"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15918"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15918"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/afa21730-92af-4160-acc1-a1af6bbd7a82.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/afa21730-92af-4160-acc1-a1af6bbd7a82.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1430,"height":699}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:58:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:58:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"typ